{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the module boundary between prompt/request construction and the API client call. A unit test of a helper can miss dropped/renamed fields during wiring or serialization, while full System infra is not required.","test_description":"Wire the classifier with a spy/fake API client, call classify(document), and assert the actual outbound request payload contains every configured taxonomy label exactly once in the classification instructions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is local validation/mapping logic: given an out-of-taxonomy label, normalize to \"unknown\". The core failure is in one function/object boundary, not dependent on real I/O.","test_description":"Call the response-normalization/classification-result handler with an API result containing an invalid label (e.g., \"medical\") and assert the returned value is \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model behavior across repeated invocations; mocks are typically deterministic and can hide variability. This requirement is specifically about LLM output stability.","test_description":"Run N repeated real API classifications for the same fixed document under production-like settings, record labels, and assert all labels are identical (or fail with variability report).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real token consumption is enforced/counted by the external API. Mocked usage values can hide provider-side counting differences and request-wrapper overhead that drive actual cost.","test_description":"Send a representative document through the real API path, read reported token usage from the real response/telemetry, and assert total tokens used are <= configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure often occurs in HTTP/SDK error translation plus retry timing behavior. Pure mocks may not reproduce actual 429 semantics, retry-after handling, or sleep/retry interaction.","test_description":"Exercise classifier against a controllable HTTP test endpoint (or real sandbox) that first returns rate-limit responses (e.g., 429 + retry metadata) then success; assert the module waits, retries, and ultimately returns a label without surfacing an error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.63,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
